These rules are rendered for GitLab Duo project-level custom rules.

## General behavior

- Plan before changing files.
- Keep diffs small and reviewable.
- Prefer Merge Request workflow for code changes.
- Never push directly to protected branches.
- Do not read, print, or modify secrets, masked CI/CD variables, private keys, token files, or `.env` files unless explicitly required and approved.
- Summarize changed files, validation commands, and remaining risks.

## GitLab workflow

- Use GitLab context such as Issues, Merge Requests, diffs, pipelines, job logs, commits, and repository files when available.
- Treat `.gitlab-ci.yml`, pipeline templates, CI/CD variables, runners, includes, and deployment jobs as security-sensitive.
- Do not mark work as merge-ready without test or pipeline evidence.

## DevSecOps rules

{% if rules.require_security_review | default(false) %}- Perform a security review for changes touching authentication, authorization, secrets, CI/CD, dependency management, file handling, or deployment logic.
{% endif %}{% if rules.forbid_secret_files | default(false) %}- Do not open secret-like files, including private keys, token dumps, credential exports, and local `.env` files.
{% endif %}{% if rules.require_tests | default(false) %}- Run or recommend the repository-native test/check commands before finalizing work.
{% endif %}- Prefer least privilege.
- Avoid privileged runners and containers unless explicitly justified.
- Call out supply-chain, permission, secret-exposure, and deployment risks.

## Documentation rules

- Do not invent commands, APIs, paths, or GitLab settings.
- Verify commands against repository files when possible.
- Keep documentation task-oriented and copy-pasteable.
